                    <headtext>Preface</headtext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </head>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation is a unique, and important, part of the
                        federal judiciary.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel exists to decide a single question: Where can cases pending in more than one
                        district best be heard for pretrial proceedings?
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Its members include judges from around the country who already have one full-time job as
                        district or circuit judge.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel handles thousands of cases and provides one of the most important means of
                        efficient and fair case management in the federal judiciary.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It regularly meets for one day of hearings a month and has, since its inception, handled
                        over 2,700 separate dockets and tens of thousands of cases.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>This work is in some ways the reincarnation of my earlier work on the Panel, <csc>
                        Multidistrict Litigation</csc>, published in 1985 and long out of print.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>This new work covers the ascendent role of the Panel and many of its significant
                        accomplishments during the past decades and provides detailed annotations to the Multidistrict
                        Litigation statute, <cite.query w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ"
                                                        w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                                                        ID="I49fbb5a0680811e8afdbaa41d3b28a1d">28 U.S.C.A. §
                            1407</cite.query>.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel is publishing many of its decisions, and this work reviews those decisions and
                        analyzes and explains the ins and outs of practice before the Panel.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel continues to play a central role in complex, multidistrict litigation, and
                        recent legislation, including the Class Action Fairness Act of 2005, only enhances its ability
                        to manage litigation.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>This book is intended to provide guidance for the lawyer or party who faces the potential
                        transfer of a case filed in the home district and now subject to transfer anywhere in the
                        country.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Because of the fundamentally practical nature of the Panel&apos;s mission, this book tries
                        to answer as many of the practical questions litigants face.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>It is not a scholarly treatise—it is without apology a practice manual.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In some cases, all this book may do is guide the reader to the Panel Rule that answers the
                        question.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
